SUMMARY 

Catalyst
   Ovum view
   Key messages
  


THERE IS AN INCREASING DEMAND FOR SMARTER MUNICIPAL SERVICES 

Municipal infrastructure creates a huge system of systems
    
Numerous infrastructure types...
     ...share common attributes...
     ...yet fail to interconnect or pool resources
     Municipal services are huge systems of systems
    
Addressing infrastructure inefficiencies and disconnects is long overdue
    
Investment capital is limited
     Services workforces are aging
     Cultural barriers are pervasive
     Citizen participation is low
     Policies failed to drive investment
    
Smart technology automates and connects infrastructure
    
Smart technology addresses infrastructure inefficiencies
     Smart technology empowers and interconnects diverse stakeholders by
     improving a system's intelligence
     True interconnectivity comes by merging different smart systems into a
     system of systems
    



CAREFUL PLANNING AVOIDS THE SUB-OPTIMIZATION OF SMART SYSTEMS 

Smart deployments are typified by constraints; the answer is to create a
   detailed model of requirements
    
Sub-optimization of any sub-system can have dire consequences
     Modeling requirements requires a view of the entire enterprise
     architecture
     The economics of smart must strike a smart balance
     Optimizing investments is an iterative process
    



A HIERARCHICAL APPROACH TO PROJECT PLANNING HELPS MANAGE COMPLEXITY 

Political, economic, and social interests must all be served by smart
   infrastructure projects
    
Understand citizens' requirements and engage in the long term
     Citizens are served by multiple asset owners
     A long-term holistic view is often overlooked due to political
     expediency
     Asset regulation must be for the long term
    
Smart brings together previously disparate groups within an organization
   Identify functional requirements in the context of a system of systems
   Legacy systems are unlikely to handle smart functionality
    
Smart automation relies on dynamic analytics and strong information
     governance
    
Planning what components to deploy reduces costs and complexity
  


CASE STUDY: SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA EDISON 

New and disruptive technology required close management
   Smart metering is a complex system of systems that required modeling at
   an early stage
   IBM Rational helped SCE do more with less
  


RECOMMENDATIONS 

u201cSmartu201d is about the citizen, not technology
   A well-executed plan reduces the risk of sub-system sub-optimization
   Managing business requirements is pivotal
   Technology can help or hinder
  


